{
  "texts": [
    "There are several proposals for input embeddings, which can be classified into context-independent (traditional) and context-dependent (contextualized) embeddings (Wang et al. 2020).",
    "While the former produces unique and distinct representations for each token without considering its context; the latter learns different embeddings for the same token according to its context (Fig. 2).",
    "Transformers also allow each sequential input to contain multiple embeddings.",
    "This approach is essentially a kind of early fusion (sum or concatenation) of embeddings.",
    "The papers discussed in our review bring several examples in such a direction."
  ]
}